end|#0ff|Up to 60% Democratic}}\n|{{legend|#f99|Up to 60% Republican}}\n|}]]\n[[File:Galusha A. Grow - Brady-Handy.jpg|thumb|175px|Speaker of the House<br/>[[Galusha A. Grow]]]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Changes in membership ==\nThe count below reflects changes from the beginning of this Congress.\n\n=== Senate ===\n<!--\nSorted Chronologically by date of vacancy\n-->\n{{See also|List of special elections to the United States Senate}}\n{{Ordinal US Congress Senate}}\n\n|-\n| [[List of United States Senators from Missouri|Missouri]] (3)\n| Vacant\n| Did not take seat until after Congress commenced.\n| nowrap {{Party shading/Democratic}} | [[Waldo P. Johnson]] (D)\n| March 17, 1861\n\n|-\n| [[List of United States Senators from Kansas|Kansas]] (2)\n| Vacant\n| Election not recognized by US Senate.\n| nowrap {{Party shading/Republican}} | [[James H. Lane (Senator)|James H. Lane]] (R)\n| April 4, 1861\n\n|-\n| [[List of United States Senators from Kansas|Kansas]] (3)\n| Vacant\n| Election not recognized by the Senate.\n| nowrap {{Party shading/Republican}} | [[Samuel C. Pomeroy]] (R)\n| April 4, 1861\n\n|-\n| [[List of United States Senators from Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania]] (1)\n| nowrap {{Party shading/Republican}} | [[Simon Cameron]] (R)\n| Resigned March 4, 1861, to become [[United States Secretary of War|Secretary of War]].<br/>Successor was elected.\n| nowrap {{Party shading/Republican}} | [[David Wilmot]] (R)\n| March 14, 1861\n\n|-\n| [[List of United States Senators from North Carolina|North Carolina]] (2)\n| nowrap {{Party shading/Democratic}} | [[Thomas Bragg]] (D)\n| Withdrew<ref name=\"Withdrawal\">Withdrawal\" meant that these senators announced they were withdrawing from the Senate due to their states' decisions to secede from the Union. Their seats were later declared vacant by the Senate, but some seats were actually unfilled since the beginning of this Congress on March 4, 1861.</ref> March 6, 1861; expelled later in 1861.\n| colspan=2 | Vacant thereafter\n\n